hristine</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Anne</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Jones</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG037507%2F1"><gtr:id>4A026AF4-E7E6-4273-B429-D91EF504BDA1</gtr:id><gtr:title>What makes adoptive family life work? Adoptive parents' narratives of the making and remaking of adoptive kinship.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G037507/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The postdoctoral fellowship will enable the award holder to further develop research on the topic of child adoption, an important and contested social policy issue. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The award holder's doctoral study focused on the experiences of couples who adopted children in the period between the introduction of the Adoption Act (1976) and the Adoption and Children Act (2002). This period saw rapid changes in adoption practice and the discourses surrounding adoption. These changes fed into debates about the State's role in regulating and mediating the transfer of children from one family to another as well as the nature of the 'family' itself, issues which remain controversial today. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The aims of the postdoctoral fellowship are to: &lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>submit for publication, in high profile national and international peer reviewed journals, a series of papers from the award holder's doctoral thesis;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>disseminate research findings from the award holder's doctoral thesis to a range of audiences including policy makers, statutory and voluntary service providers, academics and adoption service users; &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>further develop the award holder's teaching and research skills; &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>enable the award holder to develop proposals for further research funding within the field of child adoption. &lt;/li>
